      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay, i hear you on the bias thing. let's drop the loaded words then. \n\nlet's look at it purely from an operational efficiency standpoint. my concern is that our entire current architecture—the predictive modeling, the just-in-time scheduling, the automated logistics layering—is built entirely around the high-predictability, high-density infrastructure of our SE Asia hubs. \n\nif we introduce nodes in regions where the infrastructure development is less uniform or where institutional oversight is historically less consistent, does that create a mathematical risk of systemic failure for the *entire* network? basically, if we move to these less mature markets, does the increased variance in their operational reliability threaten the stability of our existing, highly optimized global flow? would the 'friction' from those regions be enough to break the efficiency of the whole system?",
